{{about|the physical bluetooth device introduced in 2015|the Facebook advertising software retired in 2009|Facebook Beacon}} The '''Facebook Bluetooth Beacon''' is a hardware [[beacon]] released by [[Facebook]] in 2015. The beacon uses a [[bluetooth]] connection to communicate with the [[Facebook app]] on the user's smartphone, informing it of the phone's location.<ref name="nfcworld">{{cite web | url=http://www.nfcworld.com/2015/02/02/333845/facebook-test-bluetooth-beacons-new-york/ | title=Facebook to test Bluetooth beacons in New York | work=NFC World | date=2 February 2015 | accessdate=30 July 2015 | author=Boden, Rian}}</ref> The technology allows location-specific advertising to be pushed to the user's Facebook feed.<ref name="nfcworld"/>
In June 2015, Facebook gave free beacons to a number of businesses in the United States.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.independent.ie/opinion/comment/beacons-a-new-marketing-ploy-or-big-brother-with-bells-and-whistles-31404026.html | title=Beacons - a new marketing ploy or big brother with bells and whistles? | publisher=Independent.ie | date=26 July 2015 | accessdate=30 July 2015 | author=Dempsey, Steve}}</ref>
==See also== * [[Bluetooth low energy beacon]] * [[Eddystone (Google)|Eddystone]]
