[[File:Pasture at Carnagh East - geograph.org.uk - 964628.jpg|Farm at Carnagh East|thumb]] {{Location map | Island of Ireland | relief = yes | width = 250 | caption = Geographical centre of Ireland | lat_deg = 53.5 | lon_deg = -8 | labe1 = Geographical centre }} The '''geographical centre of Ireland''' is in the townland of Carnagh East ({{Lang-ga|An Charnach Thoir}}), [[County Roscommon]] on the western shore of [[Lough Ree]], where the 8° Meridian West meets the 53°30' North Latitude. It is opposite the Cribby Islands and 8.85 kilometres NNW of [[Athlone]] Town.<ref>[http://www.osi.ie/en/faq/faq3.aspx Irish Ordnance Survey faq] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120228155031/http://www.osi.ie/en/faq/faq3.aspx |date=February 28, 2012 }}</ref> [[Lecarrow]] is the closest population centre.
In [[Irish mythology]], The [[Hill of Uisneach]] (which is on the road from [[Mullingar]] to [[Athlone]], about 17.7 kilometres west of Mullingar and two kilometres from the village of Loughanavally) was generally considered to be the ceremonial centre of [[Ireland]], though at times the [[Hill of Tara]] was also regarded in a similar manner. Up to 2007, a fire was lit every [[May Day]] and a Mass was celebrated on the hill of Uisneach.<ref>[http://www.realirishfood-recipes.com/ireland-facts-geography.html Geography of Ireland; facts]</ref>
