[[Category:Countries in Africa|*]] [[Category:Mountains of Africa|*]] [[Category:Africa-related lists|high]] [[Category:Lists of countries by geography|Highest point]] [[Category:Lists of highest points|Africa]] [[Category:Extreme points by country| ]] [[Category:Geography of Africa|Highest points]] [[Category:Lists of highest points in Africa]]

The '''List of African words in Jamaican Patois''' notes down as many [[loan words]] in [[Jamaican Patois]] that can be traced back to specific [[African languages]]. Most of these African words have arrived in Jamaica through the enslaved Africans that were transported there in the era of the [[Atlantic slave trade]]. The majority of Africans that survived slavery were in Jamaica were of [[Akan language|Akan]] descent, thus most the loan words were from Akan words<ref>Cassidy FG: Multiple etymologies in Jamaican Creole.
Am Speech 1966, 41:211-215</ref> {| class="wikitable sortable" !Patwa !Language !Original word !Description |- |[[Accompong]] |Akan |Acheampong (or Akropong) |[[Asante dialect|Ashanti]] surname, which means destined for greatness. "Akropong" comes from the conjugation of the Akan words "kro" and "pɔn" meaning "Great City." |- |[[Ackee]], akee |Akan |Ánkyẽ |"a type of food/fruit", "cashew fruits"<ref name="caspg3">{{Harvcoltxt|Cassidy|Page|2002|p=3}}</ref> |- |Adopi |Akan |Adópé |Ghost, often written in Jamaican English as "[[duppy]]"<ref name="caspg4">{{Harvcoltxt|Cassidy|Page|2002|p=4}}</ref> |- |Adrue |Akan, Ewe |Adúru, adrú |"powder, medicine, drug"<ref name="caspg4" /> |- |Afasia, afasayah |Akan, Ewe |Afaséw, afaséɛ |"inferior wild [[Yam (vegetable)|yam]]"<ref name="caspg4" /> |- |Afu |Akan |Afúw |"yam" or "plantation"<ref name="caspg5">{{Harvcoltxt|Cassidy|Page|2002|p=5}}</ref> |- |Ahpetti |Akan |O-peyi |A certain amulet<ref name="caspg6">{{Harvcoltxt|Cassidy|Page|2002|p=6}}</ref> |- |Akam |Akan | |A wild and inferior yam |- |Anansi |Akan, Ewe |Anansi |"Spider"<ref name="McWhorter 2000">{{Harvcoltxt|McWhorter|2000|p=77}}</ref> also name Akan [[Anansi|folktale character]]. |- |Adru |Akan | |a medica herb |- |Bafan |Akan |Bɔfran |a baby or toddler. A child that did not learn to walk between ages two and seven.<ref name="caspg20">{{Harvcoltxt|Cassidy|Page|2002|p=20}}</ref> |- |Broni |Akan |[[Oburoni]] |a white person<ref name="caspg20" /> |- |Casha |Akan, English |Kasɛ́, acacia |"thorn"<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Cassidy|Page|2002|p=93}}</ref> |- |Dookunu |Akan (Asante Twi) |[[Kenkey|Dɔkono]] |(also known as blue draws or tire leaf in Jamaica) food, a dessert item similar to bread pudding.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Cassidy|Page|2002|p=155}}</ref> |- |Dopi, dupi |Akan |Dupon (odom tree root) |"ghost" |- |Doti |Akan | |"ground"<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Institute of Jamaica|2000|p=42}}</ref> |- |Cocobay |Akan |Kokobé |"leprosy"<ref name="McWhorter 2000" /><ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Cassidy|Page|2002|p=112}}</ref> |- |Foo-fool |Akan (Ashanti Twi) |Ɛfooh |Foolish or inferior |- |Gyinal |Akan (Ashanti Twi) |Gyinaa |Someone that is not taken seriously, a stupid person. A con-man (in Jamaica only) |- |Kaba-kaba |Akan, Yoruba, Ewe | |"unreliable, inferior, worthless"<ref name="kabakaba">{{Harvcoltxt|Allsopp|Allsopp|2003|p=323}}</ref> |- |Kongkos |Akan | |"gossip"<ref name="McWhorter 2000" /> |- |Mumu |Akan, Ewe, Mende, Yoruba | |"dumb", "stupid"<ref name="McWhorter 2000" /><ref name="mumu">{{Harvcoltxt|Mittelsdorf|1978|p=34}}</ref> |- |Nana |Akan | |"grandparent"<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Cassidy|Page|2002|p=315}}</ref> |- |Odum |Akan | |a type of tree<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Cassidy|Page|2002|p=328}}</ref> |- | rowspan="2" |Obeah |Akan (Ashanti Twi) |Ɔbayi |"witchcraft"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=eHGXa2YSOrEC&dq=VOODOOS+AND+OBEAHS:+Phases+of+West+India+Witchcraft+JOSEPH+J.+WILLIAMS,+S.J.&source=gbs_navlinks_s&redir_esc=y|title=Voodoos and Obeahs: Phases of West India Witchcraft|last=Williams|first=Joseph John|publisher=Library of Alexandria|year=|isbn=9781465516954|location=|pages=90|language=en}}</ref> |- |Igbo |ọbiạ |"doctoring", "mysticism"<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Eltis|Richardson|1997|p=88}}</ref> |- |Opete |Akan | |"vulture"<ref name="caspg20" /> |- |Paki |Akan |apakyi |calabash<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Cassidy|Page|2002|p=335}}</ref> |- |Patu |Akan | |"owl"<ref name="caspg20" /> |- |Poto-poto |Akan, Igbo, Kongo and Yorubo | |"mud", "muddy"<ref name="McWhorter 2000" /> |- |Red-eye |Akan |ani bere |envy |- |Se |Akan, Igbo, English |Se, si, say |that<ref name="se">{{Harvcoltxt|Menz|2008|p=12}}</ref> |- |Backra |Efik |Mbakára |"white man"<ref name="McWhorter 2000" /><ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Cassidy|Page|2002|p=18}}</ref> |- |Juk |Fula |Jukka |"poke", "spur"<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Cassidy|Page|2002|p=153}}</ref><ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Watson|1991|p=10}}</ref> |- |Akara |Igbo, Akan, Yoruba |àkàrà |Type of food<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Cassidy|Page|2002|p=4}}</ref> |- |Attoo |Igbo |átú |"chewing s